                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12980841" author="scode" created="Wed, 12 Jan 2011 18:07:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I agree in general, unless the intent is to make out-of-the-box stress testing on memory-bound workloads optimized.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In particular I agree about being queued in the kernel, and even further down on devices or RAID controllers. Propagating outstanding I/O requests all the way down, within reason, is key to saturating the capacity of underlying spindles.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12980847" author="jbellis" created="Wed, 12 Jan 2011 18:24:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, this sounds like a pretty straightforward win.  Have you done testing on better values, Stu?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12981625" author="stuhood" created="Fri, 14 Jan 2011 04:08:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Based on IO/seek bound tests on two machines with 4 and 12 drives in RAID-0 and RAID-10, we saw the best performance with around 20 threads per drive. Not everyone will be completely IO bound though (hopefully &lt;em&gt;something&lt;/em&gt; is in cache), so perhaps a better recommended value is 16 threads per drive. I&apos;ll write a new blurb for the config file.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12981881" author="jbellis" created="Fri, 14 Jan 2011 19:14:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;committed, thanks!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12981903" author="hudson" created="Fri, 14 Jan 2011 19:55:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Integrated in Cassandra-0.7 #157 (See &lt;a href=&quot;https://hudson.apache.org/hudson/job/Cassandra-0.7/157/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://hudson.apache.org/hudson/job/Cassandra-0.7/157/&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;br/&gt;
